Q: "How would you scale to 10,000 users?"
Answer:

"I'd implement three key strategies. First, database indexing—we already have compound indexes 
on (doctorId, date) which reduced appointment queries by 95%, from 200ms to under 10ms. Second, 
load balancing with Nginx—deploy 3 backend instances behind Nginx using round-robin distribution.
Each server handles 3,333 users instead of 10,000, reducing CPU from 100% to 33%.
Third, WebSocket clustering with Redis—use Socket.IO's Redis adapter so messages sync across
all servers. Without it, User A on Server 1 couldn't message User B on Server 2. Redis acts
as a pub/sub hub, enabling real-time chat across distributed instances. We'd also use sticky 
sessions (IP hash) to keep WebSocket connections stable."



Q: "Explain compound indexing."
Answer:

"Compound indexes are multi-field indexes that optimize queries with multiple conditions. 
For example, our dashboard queries appointments by both doctorId AND date. Without an index, 
MongoDB scans all 50,000 documents linearly—taking 200ms. With appointmentSchema.index({ doctorId: 1, date: 1 }), 
MongoDB creates a sorted B-tree structure that allows binary search, jumping directly to matching documents in under 
10ms. That's a 95% performance improvement. The order matters—we index doctorId first because we always filter by
doctor, then date narrows it down further."



Q: "What's the Redis adapter doing?"
Answer:

"The Redis adapter enables Socket.IO to work across multiple servers. By default, socket.emit() 
only sends to clients connected to the same Node.js instance. In a load-balanced setup with 3
 servers, users on different servers can't communicate. The Redis adapter solves this by publishing
  all emissions to a central Redis pub/sub channel. When Server 1 emits a message, Redis broadcasts it to 
  Servers 2 and 3, which then emit to their connected clients. This creates a unified Socket.IO namespace 
  across all instances, enabling seamless real-time chat regardless of which server users connect to."

